defaultIan Odefault’defaultDonnelldefault: Yes. Typically what will happen is that the private sector company will be allowed to set up as part of the local authority scheme, as an admitted body, which means that the benefits for the employee would be the same. However, the problem with it is that the employer contribution rate might well be different within that admitted body—an actuary will look at things like the life expectancy of the individuals working for the company where the transfer has taken place—and that could make it very expensive to be a member of that scheme. It goes back to what I was saying earlier on. Sometimes it is better to manage that risk by capping the contributions that the contractor has to make towards the costs of the pensions, and meeting them through the council’s own resources; it can work out more cheaply. 
